AutoGluon: A revolutionary framework for landslide hazard analysis
Wenwen Qi a,b, Chong Xu a,b,*, Xiwei Xu a
a National Institute of Natural Hazards, Ministry of Emergency Management of China, Beijing, 100085, China b Southern Yunnan Observatory for Cross-block Dynamic Process, Yuxi Yunnan, 652799, China

ARTICLE INFO
Keywords: AutoGluon Machine learning Landslide hazard analysis Coseismic landslides Jiuzhaigou earthquake

ABSTRACT
Landslide hazard analysis is important to mitigate possible landslide hazards and ensure sustainable development of society and economy. Integrating machine learning models into landslide hazard analysis is a common but challenging task for researchers in general. In this work, we introduce a revolutionary framework, the Amazon's AutoGluon, a new open-source library of machine learning models, to analyze landslide hazards related to the 2017 Jiuzhaigou earthquake in west China. We use 11 mathematical models in the AutoGluon to perform the analysis. For each model, the coseismic landslide inventory and 10 environmental and triggering factors are used as model inputs to perform landslide hazard analysis. These 10 factors are altitude, slope, aspect, slope position, distance parallel to the seismogenic fault, distance vertical to the seismogenic fault, distance to the epicenter, lithology, distance to rivers, and distance to roads. The same number (4,834) of random points in landslide and non-landslide areas are selected, 70 % of which are used as training points, and the remaining 30 % used as validation points. It takes 47.33 s for data preprocessing and model training for 11 machine learning models and the best result measured by Roc-AUC score is 0.94. Our work shows that AutoGluon can greatly improve the efÔ¨Åciency of landslide hazard analysis.

1. Introduction
Coseismic landslides are one of the most frequent and serious geologic hazards in mountainous regions in the world (Froude and Petley, 2018). Landslide hazard mapping is crucial data to show the time and location of potential landslides and is of great signiÔ¨Åcance for risk analysis and disaster preparedness (Jibson et al., 2000).
Where and when landslides occur are determined by internal environmental and external triggering factors (Keefer and Larsen, 2007). Internal environmental factors include slope, geology, hydrology, soil or rock mechanical strength conditions, etc., which determine the spatial susceptibility of landslides (Xu et al., 2012a). External triggering factors are seismic activity, meteorological conditions, and anthropogenic interventions (Flentje et al., 2007) that determine the time, location and magnitude of landslides (Fell et al., 2008).
Landslide susceptibility analysis is a quantitative or qualitative assessment of where landslides may occur in a region (Fell et al., 2008). Landslide susceptibility indicates the preference of a geologic unit (a slope) to experience landslides given a certain combination of internal environmental factors (Reichenbach et al., 2018). However, the time and especially the magnitude of a landslide are determined by the triggering

factors. By adding external triggering factors, landslide hazard mapping could quantitatively or qualitatively predict the time and magnitude of landslides in a region (Fell et al., 2008; Guzzetti et al., 2005).
Quantifying the relation between internal environmental and external triggering factors and landslide inventories is the fundamental way in landslide hazard analysis. (Xu et al., 2012a; Hong et al., 2015). Landslide inventories are landslide distribution maps possibly with other attributes such as time of occurrence, geology of the slope, speed, area, volume etc. (Harp et al., 2011). Physical (Jibson et al., 2000) and statistical models are two major ways to establish the relation between landslide inventories and environmental and triggering factors. To perform physical models, extensively detailed in-situ parameters are needed as model inputs. In comparison, statistical models (often used interchangeably as machine learning models) are much easier and more Ô¨Çexible and are thus widely used in landslide hazard analysis.
For statistical models, landslide inventory is used as a dependent variable and environmental and triggering factors are used as independent variables (Xu et al., 2012b). The logic of using machine learning models to perform landslide hazard analysis is that locations with similar environmental and triggering conditions to landslide sites may also be prone to landsliding. To perform these models, training samples are used

