By using multiple machine learning algorithms, better predictions can be achieved in ensemble learning methods than the single learning method. Random Forest is a frequently used ensemble learning method in landslide mappings that integrates many decision trees (Stumpf and Kerle, 2011). In recent years, the ensemble learning method that uses different types of techniques and classiÔ¨Åers have been used (Nguyen et al., 2019; Hong et al., 2020; Song et al., 2020). For example, support vector machine (SVM) classiÔ¨Åer or alternating decision trees (ADT) classiÔ¨Åer with different ensemble learning techniques such as bagging, boosting and stacking algorithms were constructed for landslide susceptibility analysis (Nguyen et al., 2019; Hong et al., 2020). Four tree-based ensemble classiÔ¨Åers of random forest (RF), extremely randomized tree (ERT), gradient boosting decision trees (GBDT), and

