2. Data and methods

2.1. Data

Fig. 3. ROC curve of the models used test dataset for model evaluation, RocAUC score is the area under the ROC curve.
methods in landslide hazard analysis. First, knowledge of statistical models, mathematical principles of these algorithms and data processing are required. Second, model selection, training and validation often require coding expertise to construct massive models. Third, some complex models (e.g., ensemble learning algorithms or deep learning algorithms) have numerous parameters, and determining optimal parameters poses further challenges to practitioners.
To better facilitate landslide hazard mapping, this work introduces AutoGluon to simplify regional landslide hazard analysis by using machine learning models and ensemble learning methods. AutoGluon is an open source toolkit released by the Amazon Ltd and is an easy-to-use and easy-to-extend machine learning toolkit. It provides automatic services on data processing, model selection, model architecture search and hyperparameter tuning. In this work, the coseismic landslides inventory maps and environmental factors of the 2017 Jiuzhaigou earthquake in Sichuan Province, China are used to test the performance of AutoGluon in landslide hazard analysis.

On August 8, 2017, a Ms. 7.0 earthquake struck the famous Jiuzhaigou Natural Reserve, Sichuan Province, with a focal depth of 20 km. The geographic coordinate of the epicenter is 33.2N 103.82E, near the Bimang Village, ~5 km west of this center of the natural reserve.
Landslide inventory maps of the 2017 Jiuzhaigou Earthquake in this work are from Xu et al. (2018), Tian et al. (2019a) and Ma et al. (2019). By using high-resolution remote sensing images before and after the Jiuzhaigou earthquake, 4834 coseismic landslide polygons were manually interpreted in an area of 434 km2 and validated by Ô¨Åeld investigations (Fig. 1, c). The total coverage area of these coseismic landslides is 9.63 km2, and the density of landslide points is 11.13/km2 (Xu et al., 2018; Tian et al., 2019a; Ma et al., 2019).
To perform landslide susceptibility analysis, this work uses the same sample dataset and same ratios of training and validating samples with Ma et al. (2019). Within the study area, 4834 random points of landslides and the same number of random points of the non-landslide area are selected. Landslide sample points are randomly selected based on 4834 landslide polygons. Non-landslide sample points are randomly selected in the 100 m buffer zone around the landslide sample points. In total, 70 % of sample points (6768) are used as training points and the remaining 30 % (2899) are used as validation data to evaluate the performance of the models. This work integrates 10 environmental factors to perform landslide hazard analysis for the 2017 Jiuzhaigou earthquake. 10 dependent variables including altitude, slope, aspect, slope position, distance parallel to the seismogenic fault, distance vertical to the seismogenic fault, distance to the epicenter, lithology, distance to rivers, and distance to roads are used (Table 1). At any random points (samples), there are 10 independent variables and a binary independent variable derived from the landslide inventory.
2.2. Methods
Machine learning models in this work are embedded in the AutoGluon and are used to perform landslide hazard analysis. AutoGluon is integrated in Python 3.7 based on the Linux operating system with NVIDIA GeForce GTX 1080 Ti GPU (12 GB memory). It was developed and distributed by the Amazon Co. Ltd., and provides a platform for automated design and use of machine learning models for various researchers.
AutoGluon has the capacity to automatically optimize many procedures for machine learning models including data pre-processing, modelarchitecture search, hyper-parameter tuning, etc. The data preprocessing procedure on the platform involves classifying and formatting the input sampling data. Model-architecture search involves automating architecture engineering, which enables developers to Ô¨Ånd the best design for their machine learning models. Hyper-parameters tuning

105

W. Qi et al.

involves searching and selection of optimal architecture of the machine learning model.
This study uses the AutoGluon's Tabular Prediction function to map coseismic landslide hazards. The Tabular Prediction function uses structured data (csv or txt format, etc.) to achieve classiÔ¨Åcation or regression. Each column of the structured data represents a feature of the samples, and each row is a sample.
Python Code 1:

