Step 3. predictions ¬º predictor.predict(test_data ¬º TabularDataset(‚Äòtest.csv'))

Step 4. performance ¬º predictor.evaluate(test_data ¬º TabularDataset(‚Äòtest.csv'))
These lines of code are used to perform machine learning with AutoGluon. The Ô¨Årst four lines of the code are shown in Code 1. Step 2 is used to machine learning models training and hyper-parameters tuning. Deploying and application of the training model is performed in Step 3. Finally, training machine learning models are evaluated in Step 4.
Data preprocessing of training dataset and test dataset in the AutoGluon is implemented through the TabularDataset() module. The Ô¨Åt() module performs determining the type of prediction problems (binary classiÔ¨Åcation, multi-classiÔ¨Åcation or regression, etc.), dividing dataset (training set and validation set), selection of algorithms, model training and hyper-parameters tuning, etc. Trained models saved in the physical storage device are deployed and applied to prediction based on test dataset through predict() module. The evaluate() module is used to evaluate the performance of the trained models. For classiÔ¨Åcation task, the evaluate() module provides Accuracy, Balanced accuracy, F1 score, Roc-AUC score, Precision, Recall and Log loss. For regression task, this module calculates root mean squared error, mean squared error, mean absolute error, median absolute error and R squared. In this paper, the Roc-AUC score is used for model veriÔ¨Åcation and evaluation.

2.2.1. Data preprocessing Data preprocessing in the AutoGluon includes two consecutive stages:
model-agnostic preprocessing and model-speciÔ¨Åc preprocessing (Erickson et al., 2020). Model-agnostic preprocessing transforms the inputs into all models and standardizes the feature types of input data, including numeric, categorical, text, or date/time, etc. The text and date/time feature types are converted into suitable numeric vectors. For the missing discrete variables, AutoGluon creates an ‚ÄúUnknown‚Äù category to distinguish between the categories in which the prediction data set and the training data set are inconsistent.
Model-speciÔ¨Åc preprocessing is only applied to a copy of the data used to train a particular model. For example, input data for neural network model is preprocessed speciÔ¨Åcally. For numerical features, the median value is used to obtain the missing values, the skewed distribution of numerical features is performed quantile normalization, and all variables are normalized to zero-mean and unit variance, etc. For classiÔ¨Åcation, the category of missing data is regarded as ‚ÄúUnknown‚Äù category, and the high-cardinality features with more than 100 possible levels are classiÔ¨Åed as the ‚ÄúOther‚Äù category.
2.2.2. Model training and optimization According to the reliability of algorithms and difÔ¨Åcult levels of
training, AutoGluon sets the training sequence of machine learning models with limited training time to ensure that the training is highly reliable and concise. Each model is saved to the physical storage device immediately after training to achieve fault tolerance of training. At the same time, according to the training time restrictions set by the

Natural Hazards Research 1 (2021) 103‚Äì108
researchers, the training time of each model is allocated in advance, and the required time of each model is estimated during training process. If assigned training time is exceeded, the program will jump directly to the next model in order to guarantee predictability and execution of automatic training and hyper-parameter optimization.
2.2.3. Available machine learning algorithms The Tabular Prediction function of AutoGluon contains a series of
customized models, including neural network algorithms (Neural Networks), random forest algorithms (Random Forest), extreme random tree algorithms (Extremely Randomized Trees), K-nearest neighbor algorithm (K-Nearest Neighbors), two boosting tree algorithms (including CatBoost, LightGBM), and ensemble learning algorithms.
(1) Neural network algorithm
The neural network model is built using the MXNet Gluon. Since tabular datasets are composed of various types of data, feedforward networks are the preferred framework for building the neural network model. AutoGluon is the Ô¨Årst AutoML toolkit to use the embedding layer (Erickson et al., 2020), which uses linear short connections to connect directly to output prediction of the network. Each dense block in the neural network comprises several convolutional layers, pooling layers, ReLU activation function layers, batch normalization layers and random inactivation regularization (dropout). This work adopts the Adam optimization function with weight attenuation penalty, early-stopping and L1 loss function for training of the neural network model.
(2) Machine learning algorithms
Random forest, extremely randomized trees and K-nearest neighbor algorithms are implemented through the scikit-learn library (Pedregosa et al., 2011). Random forest and extremely randomized trees algorithms use Entropy or Gini coefÔ¨Åcient (Gini) parameters to select best features. Entropy is a measure of uncertainties in random variables. The larger of the entropy, the greater uncertainty of the random variables. Gini coefÔ¨Åcient is a feature selection method similar to information entropy, which is used to deÔ¨Åne impurity of data.
The KNN algorithm (K-nearest neighbor) is one of the simplest machine learning algorithms. It assigns to feature vectors among its k ‚Äònearest neighbors‚Äô. The number of neighboring proÔ¨Åles to be considered is equal to k. According to training instances of its k nearest neighbors, prediction is made based on the majority voting rule. For a new instance to be classiÔ¨Åed, k nearest neighbors of the instances are selected, then the major class of the k neighbors is assigned to the class of the new instance. Fast KNN search methods include brute force, k-d tree and ball tree, which are relatively simple, efÔ¨Åcient and perfectly suitable for the KNN algorithm (Nadkarni, 2016). Weighted KNN with uniform weights and distance-weighted KNN models are trained based on different weights setting methods k nearest neighbor instances.
(3) Boosting tree algorithm
The boosting tree algorithm is a machine learning method based on decision tree, optimized by forward stepwise algorithm and linear combination of trees (Li, 2019). Gradient boosting decision tree algorithm is often used optimization of boosting tree models difÔ¨Åcultly. Boosting is a method of converting weak learners to strong learners. A series of weak classiÔ¨Åers are trained based on sub-datasets obtained by splitting original datasets or changing weights of training samples. Then a series of weak classiÔ¨Åer are integrated into a strong classiÔ¨Åer. Boosting tree algorithms of AutoGluon include CatBoost and LightGBM algorithm. Both algorithms are optimized based on gradient boosting decision tree, which are able to handle huge amounts of data (Andrey et al., 2020; LightGBM, 2020; Prokhorenkova et al., 2018).

106

W. Qi et al.
(4) Ensemble learning algorithm
AutoGluon uses multi-layer stack ensembling strategy to improve accuracy of predictions. Ensembles that combine predictions from multiple models can perform individual models and drastically reduce the variance in the Ô¨Ånal predictions (Erickson et al., 2020). In order to avoid algorithm selection and hyperparameter optimization, AutoGluon simply reuses all of basic layer models as stackers. These models are any type of machine learning models and have the same hyperparameter values. The predictions of lower-layer model concatenated with the original data features are the input vectors of the stacker models. So higher-layer stackers can revisit the original data features. The last layer of the stacker model uses ensemble selection to aggregate the predictions of the stacker models in a weighted manner. By repeating the above process, the multiple-layer stacker model is obtained. Fig. 2 indicates the AutoGluon's multi-layer stacking ensembling strategy, using two stacking layers case.
3. Results
In this work, ten different machine learning models and a weighted ensemble model are used from the AutoGluon table data prediction function to perform regional landslide hazard analysis. All these models use the same data of the Jiuzhaigou landslides. The training performances of these eleven models are shown in Table 2. In the training phase, Roc-AUC score of CatBoost model is the highest for ten individual models. The weighted ensemble model has the best performance by combining predictions of those ten models.
In this work, the training time of different models ranges from 0.01 s to 23.98 s (Table 2). The mean training and the standard deviation time for these models are 4.3 s and 7.0 s, respectively. It totally takes 47.33 s for data preprocessing and model training for 11 machine learning models. The K-Neighbors require the least training time, whereas the Neural Network is the most difÔ¨Åcult training model.
We further use four criteria to measure the testing performances of these models: the Roc-AUC score (Fig. 3), precision, recall and accuracy. Among the Ô¨Årst ten models, four different models have the best performance as measured by four different criteria. The Random Forest (Gini), LghtGBM, Neural Network and LightGBM (Custom) models have the highest Roc-AUC score, precision, recall and accuracy, respectively. The AutoGluon provides a weighted ensemble model, which integrates different model outputs. This weighted ensemble model has the best performance in all measuring criteria. The Roc-AUC score, precision, recall and accuracy of the ensemble model are 94.07 % (Fig. 3), 89.12 %, 94.97 % and 88.92 %, respectively. Despite using the same data, our RocAUC score is 3 % higher than that of logistic regression model in the work of Ma et al. (2019).
4. Discussion
4.1. Faster processing and robust performance of the AutoGluon in landslide hazard analysis
Implementations of landslide hazard analysis often pose a challenge to stakeholders and there are two hurdles on the way for the general use: data preparation and model application. To carry out landslide hazard analysis, landslide inventories and other environmental maps should be derived in the Ô¨Årst place (Xu et al., 2012a). The generation of landslide inventories and selection of environmental factors require extensive expertise on landslides. Machine learning models are the most commonly used way to produce regional landslide hazard maps (Segoni et al., 2018). The logic of using machine learning models to perform landslide hazard analysis is to establish relations between environmental/triggering factors with landslide sites and use these relations to predict landslides in new regions that have known environmental/triggering factors. If all inÔ¨Çuencing factors have been updated

Natural Hazards Research 1 (2021) 103‚Äì108
after an initial earthquake, in theory, the well-trained landslide hazard models could probably predict coseismic landslides with high accuracy. In addition, by feeding nonlinear models (e.g., deep learning models) with all possible combinations of samples (landslides and corresponding inÔ¨Çuencing factors), it is promising to predict localities of coseismic landslides under new earthquakes in new regions.
To use these models, parameters embedded in the model should be selected and optimized, which requires knowledge on principles of machine learning. Moreover, model selection and construction processes are time-consuming due to low transferability of machine learning models (Tian et al., 2019b; Cao et al., 2020).
The AutoGluon Tabular Prediction function was used to map regional landslide hazards after the 2017 Jiuzhaigou earthquake. The Tabular Prediction function includes 11 machine learning models (Erickson et al., 2020) including neural network algorithms, machine learning algorithms, boosting tree algorithms, and ensemble learning algorithm. This platform can automatically select proper models and optimize model parameters according to training samples. In addition, this platform can integrate different model outputs into a weighted ensemble model and further improve the results, as shown in our work. The accuracy of seismic landslide hazard assessment based on AutoGluon is higher than traditional machine learning methods. In this case study, the highest Roc-AUC score of 11 models trained based on AutoGluon is 94.07 %, which is signiÔ¨Åcantly better than the results of Ma et al. (2019) by using the same data.
To carry out landslide hazard analysis, this work uses a binary independent variable of landslide/non-landslide and groups of other environmental variables with continuous or discrete values as independent variables are. The input of the AutoGluon Ô¨Åts the data structure required for landslide hazard analysis well. The structured dataset to perform regional landslide hazard analysis can be easily used by the AutoGluon Tabular Prediction function.
The easy implementation of landslide hazard analysis based on the AutoGluon can greatly reduce time required to select, tune and train the model. AutoGluon provides support versions of CPU and GPU. This work uses 11 models of AutoGluon, on which training time of most selected models is only a few seconds (mean time of 4.3 s). The training and hyperparameter optimization of the 11 models in this work takes only 47.33 s, which effectively improves the operation efÔ¨Åciency. In addition, function modules of AutoGluon are highly integrated with multiple functions such as data preprocessing, algorithm construction, model training, hyperparameter optimization, and model evaluation. Researchers can use machine learning models, neural network models and so forth with only 4 lines of code. The model parameters are adjusted and optimized within the speciÔ¨Åed search space, and model veriÔ¨Åcation and evaluation are performed based on multiple types of indicators. AutoGluon adopted in this study can help landslide researchers from tedious coding and focus on solving professional problems.
4.2. Limitations
AutoGluon is still in its early developmental stage and supports a limited number of algorithms within the Linux and MAC operation system. Tabular data prediction, image classiÔ¨Åcation, target detection, and text classiÔ¨Åcation are four task types supporting by the platform. For the tabular data prediction function, there are 7 algorithms, which can extend to 11 models by adjusting the parameters. In addition, the documentation of AutoGluon remains not perfect at present (https:// autogluon.mxnet.io/index.html). The speciÔ¨Åc content of the parameters and tools are not sufÔ¨Åciently described yet.
5. Conclusions
This article illustrates the potential of applying AutoGluon to seismic landslide hazard analysis. Compared with previous studies that use the same dataset, the result of the landslide hazard analysis with AutoGluon

107

W. Qi et al.
has higher accuracy. In addition, AutoGluon can automatically select algorithms, train models and optimize model hyperparameters with high efÔ¨Åciency, accuracy and robust results. This platform can be easily employed by researchers with little coding expertise to map regional landslide hazards.
To test this approach, this work integrated 10 environmental factors to map landslide hazard analysis for the 2017 Ms. 7.0 Jiuzhaigou Earthquake, China. Of these 10 factors, the distance parallel to the seismogenic fault, distance vertical to the seismogenic fault, and distance to the epicenter are quantitative descriptions of the seismic triggering factors. Precipitation is ignored in this work, because of the main inÔ¨Çuence of earthquake and large-scale co-seismic landslides. Precipitation is the main factor of post-seismic landslides (Khan et al., 2013). At a future stage, precipitation will be considered as the main triggering factor for study of surface recovery at co-seismic landslides. Although it is not possible for this work to predict the time when these co-seismic landslides occur, this set of parameters have certain frequency or recurrence period in this speciÔ¨Åc geologic condition. Therefore, this work is a test of landslide hazard analysis. Similarly, AutoGluon can also be used in other types of regional landslide analysis, such as automatic landslide identiÔ¨Åcation and landslide susceptibility mapping.
